    body: "Sts. Perpetua and Felicity (d. 203 AD) were catechumens in Carthage who were arrested under the persecution of Emperor Septimius Severus. Perpetua, a well-educated noblewoman with an infant son, kept a prison diary recording her visions and her father's desperate pleas for her to apostatize. Felicity, her slave, gave birth in prison just days before their execution. Together they were thrown to wild beasts and then killed by the sword in the amphitheater. Their account, the Passion of Perpetua and Felicity, is one of the most important documents of the early Church.",
